SIMPLE: top
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Top
<hw>Top</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[CF. OD. <ets>dop</ets>,
<ets>top</ets>, OHG., MNG., & dial. G. <ets>topf</ets>; perhaps akin to
G. <ets>topf</ets> a pot.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A child's toy,
commonly in the form of a conoid or pear, made to spin on its point,
usually by drawing off a string wound round its surface or stem, the
motion being sometimes continued by means of a whip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rope Making)</fld> <def>A plug, or conical block of
wood, with longitudital grooves on its surface, in which the strands of
the rope slide in the process of twisting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Top</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Top
<hw>Top</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>top</ets>; akin
to OFries. <ets>top</ets> a tuft, D. <ets>top</ets> top, OHG.
<ets>zopf</ets> end, tip, tuft of hair, G. <ets>zopf</ets> tuft of hair,
pigtail, top of a tree, Icel. <ets>toppr</ets> a tuft of hair, crest,
top, Dan. <ets>top</ets>, Sw. <ets>topp</ets> pinnacle, top; of
uncertain origin. Cf. <er>Tuft</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The highest
part of anything; the upper end, edge, or extremity; the upper side or
surface; summit; apex; vertex; cover; lid; <as>as, the <ex>top</ex> of a
spire; the <ex>top</ex> of a house; the <ex>top</ex> of a mountain; the
<ex>top</ex> of the ground.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The star that bids the shepherd fold,⟦br⟧
Now the <qex>top</qex> of heaven doth hold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The utmost degree; the acme; the summit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>top</qex> of my ambition is to contribute to that
work.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The highest rank; the most honorable position; the
utmost attainable place; <as>as, to be at the <ex>top</ex> of one's
class, or at the <ex>top</ex> of the school</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And wears upon his baby brow the round⟦br⟧
And <qex>top</qex> of sovereignty.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The chief person; the most prominent one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Other . . . aspired to be the <qex>top</qex> of zealots.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The crown of the head, or the hair upon it; the
head.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧From <xex>top</xex> to toe⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the stored vengeance of Heaven fall⟦br⟧
On her ungrateful <qex>top</qex> !</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The head, or upper part, of a plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The buds . . . are called heads, or <qex>tops</qex>, as
cabbageheads.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A platform surrounding the head
of the lower mast and projecting on all sudes. It serves to spead the
topmast rigging, thus strengheningthe mast, and also furnishes a
convenient standing place for the men aloft.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Wool Manuf.)</fld> <def>A bundle or ball of slivers
of comkbed wool, from which the noils, or dust, have been taken
out.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Eve; verge; point.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧He
was upon the <xex>top</xex> of his marriage with Magdaleine.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Knolles.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>The part of a cut gem between the girdle, or
circumference, and the table, or flat upper surface.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Top-boots.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A stroke on the top
of the ball.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A forward spin given to the ball by
hitting it on or near the top.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Top</xex> is often used adjectively or as the first
part of compound words, usually self-explaining; as, <xex>top</xex>
stone, or <xex>top</xex>stone; <xex>top</xex>-boots, or <xex>top</xex>
boots; <xex>top</xex> soil, or <xex>top</xex>-soil.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Top and but</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>a
phrase used to denote a method of working long tapering planks by
bringing the but of one plank to the top of the other to make up a
constant breadth in two layers.</cd> -- <col><b>Top minnow</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small viviparous fresh-water fish
(<spn>Gambusia patruelis</spn>) abundant in the Southern United States.
Also applied to other similar species.</cd> -- <col><b>From top to
toe</b></col>, <cd>from head to foot; altogether.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Top</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Top
<hw>Top</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Topped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Topping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rise aloft; to be
eminent; to tower; <as>as, lofty ridges and <ex>topping</ex>
mountains</as>.</def> <rj><au>Derham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To predominate; <as>as, <ex>topping</ex>
passions</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Influenced by <xex>topping</xex>
uneasiness.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To excel; to rise above others.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But write thy, and <qex>top</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>To strike a ball above the
center.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To rise at one end, as a yard; --
usually with <xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Top</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Top
<hw>Top</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover on the top; to
tip; to cap; -- chiefly used in the past participle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like moving mountains <qex>topped</qex> with snow.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A mount⟦br⟧
Of alabaster, <qex>topped</qex> with golden spires.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rise above; to excel; to outgo; to
surpass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Topping</qex> all others in boasting.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Edmund the base shall <qex>top</qex> the legitimate.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To rise to the top of; to go over the top
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But wind about till thou hast <qex>topped</qex> the hill.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To take off the or upper part of; to crop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Top</qex> your rose trees a little with your knife.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To perform eminently, or better than
before.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From endeavoring universally to <qex>top</qex> their parts, they
will go universally beyond them.</q> <rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To raise one end of, as a yard,
so that that end becomes higher than the other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Dyeing)</fld> <def>To cover with another dye;
<as>as, to <ex>top</ex> aniline black with methyl violet to prevent
greening and crocking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To put a stiffening piece or back on (a saw
blade).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To arrange, as fruit, with the best on top.</def>
<mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To strike the top of, as a wall, with the hind
feet, in jumping, so as to gain new impetus; -- said of a
horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To improve (domestic animals, esp. sheep) by
crossing certain individuals or breeds with other superior.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To raise one end of, as a yard,
so that that end becomes higher than the other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To cut, break, or otherwise take off the top of (a
steel ingot) to remove unsound metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>To strike (the ball) above the
center; also, to make (as a stroke) by hitting the ball in this
way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To top off</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to complete by
putting on, or finishing, the top or uppermost part of; as, <xex>to top
off</xex> a stack of hay; hence, to complete; to finish; to adorn.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to completely fill (an almost full tank) by adding more
of the liquid it already contains.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toparch</ent>⟦br⟧
